story:
On the Morning of Wednesday 6th January of dear Father/Son/Husband/Grandfather/ Uncle/ Friend Mustafa lost his battle with cancer, he was diagnosed only a month earlier in December. From diagnosis he was taken to hospital and had an operation on his spine as he was suffering back pains. We were fortunate he came home on Christmas eve to spend it with his loved ones. A few days later he was rushed back to hospital where he spent the new year and unfortunately passed.Â 

During this time we received amazing support from a Macmillan Paliative support worker named Steven who is based in Whipps Cross hospital, who was there to answer questions, administer care and support Mustafa while he was alone in hospital.Â 

We are looking to raise money for the hard workers of Macmillan Cancer Support as they have the task of helping all the brave cancer suffers either fight to recovery or care for those who's fight has come to an end.Â 

Please all take care of yourselves and make sure you stay in good health with regular check ups as some cancers are very silent and don't show symptoms till its too late as we found out. Also look after each other in these hard times!

In behalf of Mustafa's whole family. Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. I have decided to take on a marathon on Sunday May 30th Â (possibly in a virtual environment) to pay tribute to my late mother and in support of Macmillan. Â 

My Mum, Marion was diagnosed with cancer of unknown primary in lateÂ May 2019.Â Mum started experiencing symptoms just after our Dad sadly passed away in December 2018. This was Mum's second battle with cancer having been diagnosed with breast cancer in 2007. Mum was determined to fight this disease as she did back in 2007 regardless of the terminal diagnosis she was given in May 2019. She set herself goals & targets despite the odds, Mum was determined to see Christmas however in August 2019 she found out her 6th grandchild was due in April 2020 and this became her new target to meet her granddaughter.

Mum wanted to stay as independant asÂ possible, despite her deterioration she continued to stay at home and live as much of a normal life as she was able to.Â ThisÂ mustÂ have been an unimaginableÂ challenge with this disease attacking her mobility, diet, digestion and soaking up her energy every minute of everyday.

Mum dedicated her life to serve the National Health ServiceÂ with over 50 years service in various roles including Safeguarding Lead and the family know how proud she was of the NHS and carers battling this horrible Covid virus.Â 

Having helped mum since her diagnosis and throughout the pandemic really shows to me how this virus impacts so many people indirectly and charities like Macmillan now need support more then ever. Supporting people living with cancer means so much, not only to the person but their families too and to continue providing vital support despite the pandemic makes it even more important.Â 

Mum died surrounded by her family at Bassetlaw HospiceÂ on April 25th exactly a week after herÂ Granddaughter was born.Â Mum was able to meet her and have her picture taken with her, a photo we will treasure as a tributeÂ to Mum's strength, determination & loveÂ for life.

Thank you for your donation, on behalf of Marion & familiy it is greatly appreciated.

story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit the family's JustGiving page in remembrance of David Rowell.

David passed away in early 2021 at home and in the company of his immediate family after a 3-year fight with cancer. During this time, Macmillan Cancer Support frequently visited David at home and provided both emotional and practical support to him and his wife, Meg.

Cancer has a huge direct impact on the person affected and their immediate family and friends.Â The Macmillan nurses are specialist cancer nurses who can help you to understand your treatment options and support you through your cancer experience.Â Most Macmillan nurses are employed by the NHS and their posts are funded by Macmillan for a set time, often for the first three years. Any donations that we raise through this page will be used to help the charity provide specialist MacmillanÂ Cancer Support for others that may findÂ themselves in the sameÂ position.

story:
Let's bring something positive to the year!Â 

Lockdown has been tough for everyone this year but even tougher for those who have had to remain in isolation. My grandad has been undergoing cancer treatment from his home. With the government regulations and virus being so dangerous to the elderly, as a family we haven't been able to help out how we would of liked to. Instead, I would like to raise money for the people that can help him. Both of my grandparents have suffered for cancer so when I asked them which charity they would like me to run for, this is what they chose. I only started running in May this year, so a half marathon will be my biggest run to date. Any donation big or small is welcome and thank you for supporting my fundraising. Georgie xx

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support.Â

charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
Do you want to join me in making a difference? I'm raising money in aid of St John Ambulance and every donation will help. Thank you in advance for your contribution to this cause that means so much to me.

I was so looking forward to seeing you all at my bar mitzvah party on Saturday 20th of March 2021 but sadly for everyone the Covid crisis has got in the way and we have had to postpone until 19th March 2022 but I didn't want to let the day just pass by.

When it comes to celebrating a bar mitzvah we often think about the gifts that the lucky bar mitzvah boy receives but actually it is just as common for the bar mitzvah to be about giving back. That is why I have decided to raise money for St John Ambulance.

They have been excellent at helping with the Covid-19 crisis and are helping with administering the vaccine to vulnerable people. The sooner we can all be vaccinated, the better for everyone.

As we won't be able to celebrate my bar mitzvah in person this year I have decided instead to put on a short piano concert on the night when we would have been partying together.Â  I have really enjoyed playing the piano during lock down and have been working specially on some new pieces.

Everyone who donates here will receive an invitation to my Zoom concert.

All donations of any size will be very much appreciated.

I hope to see you on 20th March 2021. .

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our page for Peter.Â 

Peter suffered with congestive heart failure for many years. After his first heart attack 22 years ago, he was looked after so well within theÂ  Heart Foundation family and sadly lost his fight after a fatal cardiac arrest on the 4th January, this lead to his passing on the 5th January 2021.Â 

We cannot have any guests at the funeral & have opted for no flowers so this seems fitting to donate to such a worthy cause.Â

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
For anyone who knows me knows how big my sweet tooth is, and it's definitely grown during the pandemic. I am known amongst my friends and colleagues for always eating sweet and sugary foods! As of 17th January 2021 my challenge is to give up chocolate, sweets and sugary drinks until April 2021. This challenge will really push me to think about my own eating habits whilst raising money for a charity that desperately needs help and support right now as their research budget has been halved!Â 

I hope my willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need it most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Mam (Joan Wood) died on 31/12/20 aged 72.Â 

She loved dogs and after Penny (our much loved family labrador) died, she couldn't face getting another. A friend said, 'Why don't you puppy walk instead?' And she did.Â 

Puppy walking was a huge part of Mam's life, and she loved meeting the GDO's our puppies went to live with and meeting the new litters of puppies too.Â 

When Mam felt unable to continue to puppy walk, she kept fundraising for Guide Dogs with the Durham Branch.Â 

She would appreciate your thoughtfulness.

Thank you,Â 

LindsayÂ  and Catherine

eventName: Tor's head shave for Cancer Research
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This year has been a super tough one for everyone! ItÂ has also unfortunately meant that fundraising has decreased and also cancer treatments and testing have been delayed. 1 in 2 people will get cancer in their lifetimes, we need to keep fighting against this.Â 

On 11thÂ  March last year ( my birthday) a close family friend, Kate Bunn, was diagnosed with lung cancer, she was lucky, and was able to have treatment and is doing well! I have felt pretty helpless during this time, so this is me doing something to make a difference!

So, on my birthday this year ( 11th March) I will be shaving off my hair for cancer research (and donating it to the Little Princess Trust!). I appreciate it has been a hard year and so thank you for anything you can contribute.

I have decided as part of my charity brownie badge I would like to raise money for Cancer Research UK by running a Half Marathon (21.1km) in 7 days with my Dad, starting Sunday 17 January. This means I need to run 3km per day to achieve my goal.Â 

There are around 367,000 new cancer cases in the UK every year, that's around 1,000 every day. Unfortunately we all know of friends and family that have had cancer and my family is no different - therefore I'm keen to do my part to promote awareness and raise money.

Cancer Research UK is the world's largest independent cancer research charity and conducts valuable research into the prevention, diagnosis and treatment of the disease.Â 

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page and for supporting this incredible charity.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
On the 9th January 2021, our brave, strong mum lost her short, brutal fight against COVID-19/pneumonia.

We are shocked and heartbroken. She was the centre of all our worlds, and will remain so, always.

All of you who had the joy of knowing Mum will be aware of how selfless she was, and her work to raise money for Cancer research went on for most of her life. She always said that one day they would find a cure for cancer.Â 

This page is paired with one of mumâ€™s other passion in life, and that was the safety and protection of children. She gave money to the NSPCC most of her life and so if youâ€™d prefer to donate to that charity please click on our other page.Â 

Thank you for taking the time to read this and to donate any amount you are able to. Itâ€™s been the darkest imaginable start to the year, for us and so so many others. But in raising money in mumâ€™s name we are letting in a little light.Â 

Rest in peace our beautiful mum, wife, nanny, auntie, sister, mother-in-law and friend. Xxxx.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in peopleâ€™s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
We are all devastated at the loss of Our Benita. After a short battle with cancer, Benita passed away, peacefully at home on the 15th of January 2021 with her loving husband Stuart and her great-nieces by her side.

Benita was the life and soul of every party/event and was loved by many, many people worldwide. There will never be anyone as wonderful and kind-hearted as Benita, and she will be sadly missed by everyone whose lives she touched.

In her memory please consider donating to this fundraising effort raising vital funds for the Bradford MarieCurie hospice, a charity she held very close to her heart and fundraised for avidly throughout recent years.

story:
I have decided to set up this page in memory of Kris for a charity that really helped Kris and my parents through the last few days and hours of Kris's life. The nurses came to my parents home and helped Kris with all his care needs and always took time with him and my parents with nothing ever being problem and we couldn't have got through the last few hours without their help and support.Â  I think them being there was a comfort for Kris and my parents and we are all very greatful for the service and care they provided.

If you are able to help us in donating to this great charity in memory of Kris that would be amazing but we understand times are tough at the moment but on behalf of myself and my family i would like to thank you all for visiting this page and having Kris in your thoughts.

Thank you

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in peopleâ€™s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UKâ€™s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
eventName: Help us to save lives at sea
story:
Last year was a difficult one for everyone, enduring lock downs due to the pandemic and interrupting our daily lives, yet your local Lifeboat station in Clacton-on-Sea continues to be available 24/7, 365 days a year to help anyone who may be in trouble in and around the water.

As a charity, the RNLI depends on donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. Your local community crew of RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. Theyâ€™re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the the clock.

Our fundraising has suffered greatly over the past 12 months, so today we are launching not our lifeboats, but our JustGiving campaign to ask if you could support your local station by donating what you can.

Your kind donations will help keep our station running, maintained and always ready to launch into the rough seas to try to save lives.

For more information as to how we spend our money, please do look at the following page:Â <a href="https://rnli.org/support-us/how-your-support-helps/where-your-money-goes" target='new'>https://rnli.org/support-us/how-your-support-helps/where-your-money-goes</a>

On behalf of all the crew members in Clacton-on-Sea, we thank you for any support you can provide.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UKâ€™s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
It is with sadness we announce that Paul Freshney passed away peacefully at his home in Brentwood, Essex, on 27 December 2020.

Paul was a keen supporter of the RNLI for all of his adult life. The charity undertakes important work, and he admired the lifeboat crews for the sacrifices they make to save lives out at sea.

Paul would not want for anyone to feel obliged to make a donation. But for those who want to, a contribution to the RNLI in lieu of flowers would be appreciated.

Rose, Mark and Sara

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Nature needs us. Every second, every minute, every hour. 

I'm making the most of my time and reaching my potential to do as much as I can for my health and nature. I'm running one mile every hour, maximising the time in-between to raise money to fight for our world.

charity.description:
Weâ€™re the worldâ€™s leading independent conservation organisation. And weâ€™re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

Thatâ€™s why weâ€™re passionate about sharing the planetâ€™s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
Originally, i decided to run a half marathon for myself and to give me a target during ongoing lockdowns and my university degree. I realised that i could try and raise some money for a cause close to my heart at the same time. Climate change is something I care deeply about and is the area of science research I intend to work in once i have completed my studies. My current third year dissertation is on the use of seaweeds as viable bioplastics. WWF are an amazing charity who do a lot of work in tackling climate change but also protecting the species that are under threat from it. I would appreciate any support whatsoever that you can give to this charity. Any donation is useful and can help them fund the projects they carry out here in the UK and in the Amazon, Antarctica etc. I woluld reccomend having a look at their website if you are interested in finding out more about what their projects include and where they have been working recently.

wwf.org.uk

charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
I'm a proud adopter of the Enesikira pride of lions; part of the Mara Predator Conservation Programme thanks to my girlfriend Holly giving my adoption pack as a Christmas gift. This gift has given me the opportunity to continue supporting the work of WWF through another passion of mine, fitness. The goal is to run this marathon under 2hrs-20 and I will train to achieve it (never ran a marathon before). Attempting this while contributing to the work WWF do in protecting, conserving and securing a future for the wild world is a privilege and honour. Massive thank you to Holly for making this happen, you're the best! Thank you to everyone who donates, you're helping to tackle some of the biggest environmental challenges facing our natural world today and providing extra motivation for my journey to the Manchester marathon 2021.

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world's most important environmental challenges , safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive. Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.ukÂ

charity.name: Oxfam
story:
Trailwalker UK supports the incredible work of both Oxfam Great Britain and The Gurkha Welfare Trust.

Kitty and I walked the White Horse Trail last summer and fell in love with walking over the chalk downlands. We then moved on to the Ridgeway, walking from Marlborough to Ivinghoe Beacon, often with Izzy who was staying at home. We then went the other way on the Wessex Ridgeway, aiming for Lyme Regis before winter curtailed us. The South Downs Way will be a new and really tough challenge, walking non-stop, through the night with two of our gorgeous daughters, Izzy and Alicia.
